{{distinguish|Salumá language}} {{Infobox language |name=Enawene Nawe |nativename=Salumã |region=[[Mato Grosso]], [[Brazil]] |ethnicity=[[Enawene Nawe people]] |speakers=350 |date=2000 |ref=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrelp.org/grants/projects/index.php?lang=81 |title=Sketch grammar, texts and dictionary of Enawene-Nawe (Arawak, Brazil)|publisher=HRELP |accessdate=2009-06-03}}</ref> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=Bolivia–Parana? |iso3=unk |glotto=enaw1238 |glottorefname=Enawené-Nawé }} '''Enawene Nawe''' (Enawené-Nawé, Enawenê-Nawê, Eneuene-Mare), also known as '''Salumã''', is an [[Arawakan language]] of [[Brazil]] spoken by about 350 people in the state of [[Mato Grosso]]. Aikhenvald (1999) classifies it together with [[Terena language|Terena]] and related languages.
