{{Infobox language |name = Iñapari |nativename = |pronunciation = |states = [[Peru]] |region = |speakers = 4 |date=1999 |ref=e18 |familycolor = American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Piro languages|Piro]] |nation = Perú |iso3 = inp |glotto=inap1242 |glottorefname=Inaparic }}
'''Iñapari''' is a critically endangered indigenous South American language spoken by just four people in [[Perú]] along the [[Las Piedras River (Peru)|Las Piedras]] river near the mouth of the Sabaluyoq river. The language is already extinct in neighboring [[Bolivia]]. All four remaining speakers are bilingual in [[Spanish language|Spanish]] and none have any children, which will likely lead to its extinction once the speakers die. The Iñapari language currently has a published dictionary.<ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=36668 Datos de la lengua Iñapari.] Parker, Stephen G., compiler. 1995. Documento de Trabajo, 27. Yarinacocha: Ministerio de Educación and Instituto Lingüístico de Verano. 208 p.</ref><ref>[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_work.asp?id=42176 A sketch of Iñapari phonology] Parker, Steve. 1999. International Journal of American Linguistics 65: 1-39.</ref>
The Pacaguara (Pacahuara) dialect described by Mercier was at least ethnically distinct. (But see [[Pacaguara language]].)
